Hi Team,

I will walk through the SDM File Export API flow, its purpose, current implementation, old vs new approach, and the important classes involved.

1. Application Overview

This application is SDM File Export API. Its purpose is to export SDM catalogue/reference data from Oracle DB tables into CSV format, create a control/ready file with record count, package both files into a ZIP, and return the ZIP file to the caller.

This application is not creating or modifying business data. It is only reading existing catalogue data from Oracle DB and exporting it in file format for downstream processing.

The main exported tables are:

1. OM_CATALOGUE_SUNDRY
2. OM_CATALOGUE_SOURCE_SYSTEM
3. OM_CATALOGUE_SOURCE_SYSTEM_COVERAGE
4. OM_CATALOGUE_SDM_LOG is used only for logging successful export runs.

2. Old vs New Approach

Earlier, the SDM files were generated/pushed through the existing old process and the consuming team used to pick files from the server/Hive incoming location.

As part of the new approach, we are exposing APIs through the SDM File Export API. The consuming team can call the API, download the ZIP file, extract CSV and control file, and place/upload them to their expected server/Hive path.

There is no functional change in the data selection logic. The same table data and same filtering logic are being used. The change is mainly technical: instead of relying on the old file generation/push process, we are exposing API-based ZIP download.

3. API Endpoints

The controller is SchemaBrowserController.

Show this file:

src/main/java/com/citi/olympus/controller/SchemaBrowserController.java

@RequestMapping(value = "/citihawk/schemabrowser")

POST /citihawk/schemabrowser/exportSundry
POST /citihawk/schemabrowser/exportSourceSystem
POST /citihawk/schemabrowser/exportSourceSystemCoverage

Adhoc/latest fetch endpoints are available for:

/exportSourceSystemAdhocLatestFetch
/exportSourceSystemCoverageAdhocLatestFetch

Sundry does not appear to have a separate adhoc controller endpoint.

4. Load Type Logic

In SchemaBrowserController, each endpoint reads optional request parameter:

@RequestParam(name = "load", required = false) String load

logic
load=7  → WEEKLY load
load=1  → SPECIFIC / 1-day load
no load or other value → FULL_LOAD

Show these lines in SchemaBrowserController:

if (load != null && load.equalsIgnoreCase("7")) {
    exportTypeDTO.setType(WEEKLY);
} else if (load != null && load.equalsIgnoreCase("1")) {
    exportTypeDTO.setType(SPECIFIC);
    exportTypeDTO.setNoOfDays(Integer.parseInt(load));
} else {
    exportTypeDTO.setType(FULL_LOAD);
}

The controller then calls the service:
schemabrowserService.exportSundry(exportTypeDTO)
schemabrowserService.exportSourceSystem(exportTypeDTO)
schemabrowserService.exportSourceSystemCoverage(exportTypeDTO)

and returns the ZIP as API response using:

ResponseEntity.ok()
.header(HttpHeaders.CONTENT_DISPOSITION, "attachment; filename=...")
.contentType(MediaType.APPLICATION_OCTET_STREAM)
.body(resource)

5. Service Layer Flow

Main service implementation:

src/main/java/com/citi/olympus/service/impl/SchemaBrowserServiceImpl.java

whoe methods 
exportSundry(...)
exportSourceSystem(...)
exportSourceSystemCoverage(...)

High-level service flow:

1. Identify export type: WEEKLY / SPECIFIC / FULL_LOAD / ADHOC
2. Call repository query based on export type
3. Convert DB results into CSV rows
4. Create control file with record count
5. Zip CSV + control file
6. Update OM_CATALOGUE_SDM_LOG after successful export
7. Send success/failure email notification
8. Return ZIP file to controller

